---
import TrustLayout from "../layouts/TrustLayout.astro";
import { trust } from "../lib/trust";

// DRAFT (see src/lib/sitemap.ts): rendered at build, pruned from deploys.
// ALL-CAPS statements are unfilled facts with the expected content in
// parentheses — they must all be resolved before this section leaves draft.
//
// Section headings deliberately track the SafeBase/Drata trust-center AI
// cards ("AI Overview", "Employee AI Usage", "AI Security", "AI Training
// Data") so reviewers filling SafeBase-shaped questionnaires can map 1:1.
// The model-level list has no convention to follow — vendor-level cards are
// where the industry stops — so we set one; details live in trust.yaml
// (`aiModels`), same source the DPA and Subprocessors page draw from.
const aiTools = trust.internalTools.filter((t) => t.ai);
const models = trust.aiModels;
---

<TrustLayout
  title="AI"
  description="Where AI is used at Onetime Secret and where it never is: no AI in the product, model-level disclosure of internal tooling, and the boundary we keep."
  active="ai"
>
  <div class="page" style="max-width: 668px;">
    <div class="kicker">AI at Onetime Secret</div>
    <h1>Where AI is —<br />and isn't</h1>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        There is no AI in the product. Secret Content is never sent to, processed by, or readable
        by any AI system — ours or a vendor's — and no AI provider is a subprocessor: on the
        <a href="/subprocessors">subprocessors page</a>, AI tools appear only under internal
        tooling, listed for transparency, never in the register itself. The service has no AI
        features.
      </p>
      <p>
        We do use AI-assisted tools to build and run the company: engineering, documentation and
        policy drafting, and research. This page says which tools, which models specifically, and
        the boundary that keeps them away from customer data. Most AI pages explain the AI in the
        product; ours exists to show there is none, and to disclose the rest anyway.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section style="margin-top: 44px;">
      <div class="kicker left" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">Employee AI usage — the tools</div>
      <p class="section-intro">
        The AI-assisted tools we use internally, from the same
        <a href="/trust.yaml">trust.yaml</a> that generates the Subprocessors page. They operate
        on source code, documentation, and policy drafts — never Secret Content, Account Data, or
        other Company Personal Data.
      </p>
      <div class="tools">
        {
          aiTools.map((t) => (
            <div class="tool">
              <div class="tool-head">
                <span class="tool-name">{t.name}</span>
                {t.jurisdiction && <span class="tool-juris mono">{t.jurisdiction}</span>}
              </div>
              <p class="tool-use">{t.use}</p>
              {t.note && <p class="tool-note">{t.note}</p>}
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <div class="kicker left" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">The models, specifically</div>
      <p class="section-intro">
        Vendor names say who we pay; they don't say what actually processes our source and
        drafts, or under which terms. Trust-center convention stops at the vendor, so there is no
        standard to follow here — we list the models anyway: the exact model as the vendor names
        it, the surface it's reached through, and what we use it for. Changes to this list are
        visible as <a href="/trust.yaml">trust.yaml</a> diffs.
      </p>
      <div class="models">
        {
          models.map((m) => (
            <div class="model">
              <div class="model-head">
                <span class="model-name mono">{m.model}</span>
              </div>
              <p class="model-meta">
                {m.vendor} · via {m.via}
              </p>
              <p class="model-use">{m.use}</p>
              {m.note && <p class="model-note">{m.note}</p>}
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <div class="kicker left" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">AI security — the boundary in practice</div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The boundary is physical, not just contractual. Development and AI-assisted work happen
          on separate physical machines from production operations. The production-operations
          machines have no AI tools installed, and AI features in the software they do run — Zed,
          for example — are disabled. An AI tool cannot reach production systems or the data on
          them from the machines it runs on.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two tools sit outside our machines entirely: GitHub Copilot code review and Greptile
          run on their vendors' infrastructure against pull requests. Their access ends at
          repository contents — source code and diffs, which never include Secret Content or
          Account Data.
        </p>
        <p>
          STATE THE REVIEW PRACTICE FOR AI-ASSISTED CHANGES (whether AI-assisted code and copy
          pass through the same review and version control as any other change before reaching
          production, and who signs off).
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <div class="kicker left" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">AI training data</div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          There is no Onetime Secret model: we develop, train, and fine-tune none, so no customer
          data can be training data of ours. What remains is vendor-side: whether the providers
          above may train on our inputs. The per-model terms are recorded in the list above.
        </p>
        <p>
          STATE THE CONFIRMED TRAINING POSITION ACROSS VENDORS (once counsel confirms each
          account's tier and terms: a single sentence on whether our inputs are excluded from
          model training everywhere, and any exception).
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-top: 56px;">
      <div class="kicker left">Notices</div>
      <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 20px;">
        <div class="callout-label">If the boundary moves</div>
        <p>
          If any AI provider ever begins processing Company Personal Data — AI-assisted support
          touching customer email, say — it becomes a subprocessor <strong>before first use</strong>:
          it enters the <a href="/subprocessors">register</a> and <a href="/dpa">Schedule A</a>,
          and the thirty-day notification policy applies.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 16px;">
        <div class="callout-label">Why disclose now</div>
        <p>
          No rule requires this page. The EU AI Act's transparency obligations (Article 50) cover
          people interacting with AI systems and synthetic content, not a company's internal use
          of AI tools, and the GDPR has no AI-specific disclosure duty. We expect that to change,
          and we would rather state our practice before it does than after.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</TrustLayout>

<style>
  .section-intro {
    font: 400 14.5px/1.65 var(--sans);
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0 0 8px;
  }

  /* Tool cards — same compact format as the Subprocessors page's
     internal-tools list. */
  .tools {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .tool {
    padding: 16px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .tool-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 12px;
  }
  .tool-name {
    font: 600 15.5px var(--sans);
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .tool-juris {
    font: 400 11.5px var(--mono);
    color: var(--faint);
  }
  .tool-use {
    margin: 6px 0 0;
    font: 400 13.5px/1.6 var(--sans);
    color: var(--muted);
  }
  .tool-note {
    margin: 5px 0 0;
    font: 400 12.5px/1.55 var(--sans);
    color: var(--faint);
  }

  /* Model list — one row per model: the model ID carries the weight. */
  .models {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .model {
    padding: 16px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .model-name {
    font: 600 13.5px/1.5 var(--mono);
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .model-meta {
    margin: 5px 0 0;
    font: 400 12.5px var(--sans);
    color: var(--faint);
  }
  .model-use {
    margin: 6px 0 0;
    font: 400 13.5px/1.6 var(--sans);
    color: var(--muted);
  }
  .model-note {
    margin: 5px 0 0;
    font: 400 12.5px/1.55 var(--sans);
    color: var(--faint);
  }
</style>
